data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core 9, the Cosmos DB provider began **throwing `InvalidOperationException` on synchronous LINQ calls by default**. Your .NET 10 app worked because you opted back in with something like:

```csharp
options.UseCosmos("...", builder => builder.EnableSyncExecution());
```

**In EF Core 11, that opt-in is removed entirely.** All four methods in your repository will throw `InvalidOperationException` at runtime — there is no workaround flag.

## The fix — convert to async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- Return types become `Task<T>` / `Task`
- Methods marked `async`, suffixed with `Async`
- `ToList` → `ToListAsync`, `First` → `FirstAsync`, `Count` → `CountAsync`, `SaveChanges` → `SaveChangesAsync`
- Remove the `EnableSyncExecution()` call from your Cosmos config

You'll also need to propagate `async/await` up through every caller in the chain (controllers, services, etc.).
